      SPAC SPAC SPAC
   =20
 =20

Simplifying a bit, the way a special purpose acquisition company works is t=
hat the sponsor of the SPAC raises a pot of money by selling shares to publ=
ic investors at $10 per share. Say the sponsor offers 20 million shares, so=
 the pot of money has $200 million in it. Then she goes out and looks for a=
 private target company to merge with to take it public. Say she finds a pr=
ivate company that is worth $800 million. (The valuation of a private compa=
ny will always be uncertain, but let=E2=80=99s assume for now that the valu=
ation of=C2=A0this=C2=A0company is certain, and that it=E2=80=99s $800 mill=
ion.) If the target company is worth $800 million, and the SPAC is just a p=
ot of money with $200 million in it, then the combined company should be wo=
rth $1 billion. So the sponsor and the target company negotiate a merger in=
 which the existing shareholders of the target company get 80% of the share=
s of the combined company ($800 million worth) and the SPAC shareholders ge=
t 20% ($200 million worth). (The merger=C2=A0is sometimes called a =E2=80=
=9Cde-SPAC merger.=E2=80=9D)=C2=A0The public investors in the SPAC, who put=
 in $10 each, end up with publicly traded shares of the combined company wo=
rth $10 each.=C2=A0
If the SPAC sponsor doesn=E2=80=99t find a deal before, typically, the two-=
year deadline put on the SPAC, she has to give her public shareholders thei=
r $200 million back with interest. If she does find a deal, she has to put =
it to a vote of the public shareholders; they can vote it down if they don=
=E2=80=99t think it=E2=80=99s a good deal. Even if they vote in favor, they=
 can=C2=A0redeem=C2=A0their stock: Instead of taking new shares in the comb=
ined company, the SPAC shareholders can ask for their $10 back (with intere=
st).=C2=A0
That is the basic story, but it=C2=A0is too simplified, and=C2=A0in the rea=
l world things won=E2=80=99t quite work this way. In the real world the val=
uation of the private target company will be uncertain, and there will be a=
 negotiation about how much of the combined company the SPAC=E2=80=99s shar=
eholders should get. The SPAC sponsor might reasonably say: =E2=80=9CLook, =
you are a risky private company, your valuation is uncertain, and I am=C2=
=A0doing you a favor =E2=80=94=C2=A0I am providing a service =E2=80=94 by g=
iving you publicly traded stock. You and I both think that you are probably=
 worth $800 million, but I want a discount. Let=E2=80=99s do this deal as t=
hough you were worth $600 million, so the SPAC shareholders get 25%=C2=A0of=
 the company, instead of 20%.=E2=80=9D If the target company agrees, and if=
 they=E2=80=99re right that the real=C2=A0value is $800 million, then the p=
ublic investors will end up with 25% of a combined company worth $1 billion=
. They put in $200 million and got back shares worth $250 million; each of =
their public shares will be worth $12.50. And in fact at the peak of the 20=
20-2021 SPAC boom, this happened a lot: SPACs would announce deals with pri=
vate companies, and their shares would trade up, to $12.50 or higher, becau=
se the SPACs were getting a good deal.
  [1]

Now, things could go the other way. In fact there was eventually a glut of =
SPACs looking for deals, and the negotiating leverage flipped. The target c=
ompany=E2=80=99s founder might reasonably say: =E2=80=9CLook, you are a SPA=
C in a glut of SPACs, you need a deal, and I am=C2=A0doing you a favor=C2=
=A0by giving you a target. You and I both think that I am worth $800 millio=
n, but I want a premium. Let=E2=80=99s do this deal as though I was worth $=
1 billion, so your SPAC shareholders get 16.7% of the company instead of 20=
%.=E2=80=9D Then the SPAC=E2=80=99s public shareholders would get shares of=
 the combined company worth $8.33.
  [2]
=C2=A0Except that if this happened =E2=80=94 if the SPAC agreed to do a dea=
l at a value that everyone knew made the shares worth less than $10 =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0the shareholders would just say no. They would vote to reject the =
deal, or at least, they=E2=80=99d redeem their shares: Much better to get b=
ack $10 with interest than keep shares worth $8.33. SPACs can do deals at a=
 discount (if they can talk their targets into those deals!), but not at a =
premium.
Of course I am still oversimplifying. For one thing, I am still assuming th=
at everyone basically knows the valuation of the private company: The SPAC =
and the target might negotiate for a premium or discount, but the =E2=80=9C=
real=E2=80=9D value is transparent to the market. That=E2=80=99s not really=
 true, and it is not hard to find SPAC deals that traded up when they were =
announced and eventually traded down as the real value of the company becam=
e clearer. In reality it is not at all uncommon for SPAC shareholders to tr=
ade their $10 for shares that ultimately turn out to be=C2=A0worth=C2=A0les=
s than that. When that happens, the shareholders might, in hindsight, feel =
like they were deceived. The SPAC sponsor announced the deal with great exc=
itement, the shareholders believed it, they kept their shares, thinking tha=
t they=E2=80=99d be worth way more than $10, and they turned out to be wort=
h less.
But I have also oversimplified by omitting some important structural elemen=
ts of SPACs. In fact, when the SPAC sponsor raises $200 million at the very=
 beginning of this process, she=C2=A0doesn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0do it just by sel=
ling 20 million shares. She sells 20 million =E2=80=9Cunits,=E2=80=9D and e=
ach unit consists of (1) one share and (2) some number of=C2=A0warrants, op=
tions to buy another share at some higher price. (Generally the warrant exe=
rcise price is $11.50, a 15% premium to the initial price of the stock, and=
 each unit comes with a fraction of a warrant, often one-quarter or=C2=A0on=
e-third.) After the SPAC goes public, the warrants and shares will trade se=
parately. Ultimately, if the SPAC closes a deal, each=C2=A0share=C2=A0can b=
e redeemed for $10 or roll over into a share of the combined company, but e=
ach=C2=A0warrant=C2=A0can only roll over to become a warrant of the combine=
d company. And if the SPAC does=C2=A0not=C2=A0close a deal, each=C2=A0share=
=C2=A0can be redeemed for $10, but each warrant expires worthless.
Also, when the SPAC sponsor raises $200 million at the beginning of the pro=
cess, there are not just 20 million SPAC shares outstanding. In fact the SP=
AC sponsor will generally give herself 20% ownership of the SPAC =E2=80=94 =
5 million shares =E2=80=94=C2=A0for free as a reward for her efforts in set=
ting it up and finding a deal.
  [3]
=C2=A0If she fails to find a deal, those shares are canceled: She has to re=
turn $10 per share to the public shareholders, $200 million total, which us=
es up all of the money in the pot, and there=E2=80=99s nothing left for her=
. (In fact she will lose=C2=A0money, because she paid the SPAC=E2=80=99s st=
artup costs, advisory fees etc. out of her own pocket.) But if she does fin=
d a deal, her 5 million shares roll over into shares of the combined compan=
y.
(One more thing that I am omitting is that SPAC deals are traditionally don=
e alongside PIPEs, private investments in public equity, where the sponsor =
and/or some other big institutional investors put=C2=A0more money into the =
combined company=C2=A0at $10 per share. I am going to continue omitting tha=
t =E2=80=94=C2=A0and in fact as the SPAC glut got shakier PIPEs were=C2=A0n=
ot universal =E2=80=94=C2=A0but if there is a PIPE it considerably softens =
some of the criticisms in the rest of this story.)
Now let=E2=80=99s go back to the simple math, but with these more realistic=
 facts. The sponsor finds a private company worth $800 million, and they ag=
ree to a merger on exact fair-value terms. The SPAC contributes $200 millio=
n, the combined company is worth $1 billion, so the SPAC gets back 20% of t=
he combined company, which is worth $200 million. But now the SPAC has to d=
ivide up that value. There are=C2=A0not=C2=A020 million shares of the SPAC:=
 There are 25 million, the 20 million public shares and the sponsor=E2=80=
=99s 5 million free shares. Each of these shares is worth $8. The sponsor g=
ets 5 million shares worth $40 million for free, but that $40 million comes=
 directly out of the public shareholders=E2=80=99 ownership stake. They put=
 in $10 and get back shares worth $8.
Also there are the warrants. In this stylized example, where we know the st=
ock is worth $8 and the warrants are worthless unless the stock gets to $11=
.50, the warrants aren=E2=80=99t worth much. But in the real world, where s=
tocks are volatile and value is uncertain, the warrants will have some valu=
e, and that value will dilute the other holders of the combined company. Th=
e target company might say: =E2=80=9COkay fine, we are worth $800 million, =
you have $200 million, the combined company is worth $1 billion and we will=
 give you 20% of that value. But that 20% has to be divided among your shar=
es and your warrants; we are not going to give your=C2=A0shareholders=C2=A0=
20% of the company and then also let your=C2=A0warrantholders=C2=A0exercise=
 their warrants for another 20%.
  [4]
=C2=A0That would be unfair. We=E2=80=99ll give your shareholders, say, 16% =
of the combined company=E2=80=99s stock, to reflect the fact that if things=
 go well your warrantholders will get another big chunk of the stock.=E2=80=
=9D (Don=E2=80=99t worry about the exact number =E2=80=94=C2=A0it will depe=
nd on, basically, how valuable you think the warrants are, how close they a=
re to being a share of stock =E2=80=94=C2=A0but the point is that you shoul=
d attribute=C2=A0some=C2=A0value to the SPAC=E2=80=99s warrants, which will=
 reduce the value that you attribute to its stock.)
These things are problems. They suggest that if a SPAC ever agrees to a mer=
ger at=C2=A0exactly fair value=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0where the SPAC puts in $=
200 million and gets back exactly $200 million worth of the combined compan=
y =E2=80=94=C2=A0then the SPAC=E2=80=99s=C2=A0public shareholders=C2=A0are =
getting hosed. Their $10 investment turns into stock worth $8 at most, prob=
ably $7 or less. Of course they can vote no on the deal, and/or redeem thei=
r stock, and this math suggests that they always should, and that if they v=
ote yes they are somehow confused or deceived.
The simplest=C2=A0solution here is for the SPAC to negotiate such a good de=
al =E2=80=94=C2=A0and for the combined company to perform so well =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0that the shares are worth $12 anyway. Like, if the SPAC contributes $=
200 million and gets back $400 million worth of value, that=E2=80=99s plent=
y to make sure that the sponsor gets her free shares, the warrantholders ge=
t their warrants, and the public shareholders get shares worth more than $1=
0. In the peak days of SPAC enthusiasm, that kind of worked, through some c=
ombination of:
=09SPACs seemed like an attractive way to go public, so private companies=
=C2=A0were=C2=A0willing to merge with them at=C2=A0discounts;=09you needed =
a PIPE deal alongside the SPAC, so if a deal was going to get=C2=A0done the=
n target companies had to agree on a valuation that made the common shares =
worth $10
  [5]
;=09the market was going up generally;=09SPAC shareholders were particularl=
y enthusiastic, so they kept bidding up de-SPAC mergers; and=09possibly peo=
ple did not understand this stuff very clearly?

But over time, as the market stopped rising, SPACs became better understood=
, and a glut of SPACs pursued a smaller universe of good deals, these thing=
s became real problems. The deep problem with a SPAC is that the SPAC=E2=80=
=99s sponsor takes out 20% of the value of the money that she raises, and t=
he warrantholders get a cut too, and=C2=A0somebody needs to pay them that c=
ut. Either the target company pays it (by giving up more of the company for=
 the SPAC proceeds), or the public SPAC shareholders pay it=C2=A0(by gettin=
g shares worth $7 for their $10 investment). Somebody is getting a bad deal=
.
The argument above is loosely based on a well-known=C2=A02020 paper called =
=E2=80=9CA Sober Look at SPACs,=E2=80=9D by Michael Klausner, Michael Ohlro=
gge and Emily Ruan. From the abstract:
We find that costs embedded in the SPAC structure are subtle, opaque, highe=
r than has been previously recognized, and higher than the cost of an IPO. =
Although SPACs raise $10.00 per share from investors in their IPOs, by the =
time a SPAC merges with a private company to take it public, the SPAC holds=
 far less in net cash per share to contribute to the combined company. For =
SPACs that merged during our primary sample period of January 2019 through =
June 2020, mean and median net cash per share were $4.10 and $5.70, respect=
ively. Between June 2020 and November 2021, net cash per share was somewhat=
 higher but far below $10. We find that SPAC costs are not born by the comp=
anies they take public, but instead by the SPAC shareholders who hold share=
s at the time SPACs merge. These investors experience steep post-merger los=
ses, while SPAC sponsors profit handsomely.=C2=A0
Intuitively, if the =E2=80=9Cnet cash per share=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0tha=
t is, the money=C2=A0that the SPAC has in its pot, divided by the=C2=A0real=
=C2=A0number of shares including free sponsor shares and warrants =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0is $5.70, then either target companies are getting a bad deal (giving=
 up $10 of value for $5.70 of cash), or public SPAC shareholders are gettin=
g a bad deal (getting $5.70 of value for $10 of cash). And Klausner et al. =
find that it=E2=80=99s mostly the shareholders getting the bad deal. Their =
article =E2=80=9Cconcludes by suggesting that the SEC promulgate disclosure=
 requirements specific to SPAC mergers that make clear SPACs=E2=80=99=C2=A0=
costs and sponsors=E2=80=99 incentives.=E2=80=9D
But that=E2=80=99s just an academic paper. Putting his money where his mout=
h is, though, Klausner went out to sue some SPACs, and   last week he won a=
 round:

A court ruling Wednesday bolstered research that argues the true worth of b=
lank-check company mergers is often far below the typical $10-a-share valua=
tion.
The Delaware Chancery Court ruling found that the GigCapital3 Inc. special =
purpose acquisition company must face claims that public shareholders were =
denied crucial information, including how much money shares were worth in t=
he purchase of an electric vehicle manufacturer.
The GigCapital3 SPAC shareholders couldn=E2=80=99t make an informed decisio=
n on whether to cash out shares or participate in its purchase of Lightning=
 eMotors, court Vice Chancellor Lori Will ruled. =E2=80=A6
Stanford Law Professor Michael Klausner developed a financial model that ar=
gues the true value of SPAC shares are much lower than $10-a-share. He brou=
ght the court case in August 2021 against GigCapital3 alongside lawyers fro=
m Grant & Eisenhofer. The suit was a rare move for a self-described =E2=80=
=9Cobscure academic.=E2=80=9D
In the Gig3 case, the sponsor=E2=80=99s initial $25,000 investment had an i=
mplied market value at the time of the merger worth $39 million=E2=80=94a 1=
55,900% return, Klausner argued. Sponsors only earn those returns when a de=
al is completed.
Will=E2=80=99s ruling accepted Klausner=E2=80=99s calculations. Part of the=
 information GigCapital3 shareholders didn=E2=80=99t receive was that the s=
hares the SPAC used to purchase Lightning eMotors were worth around $5.25 p=
er share=E2=80=94not $10, according to Will.
=E2=80=9CIf Gig3 had less than $6 per share to contribute to the merger, th=
e proxy=E2=80=99s statement that Gig3 shares were worth $10 each was false=
=E2=80=94or at least materially misleading,=E2=80=9D she wrote. =E2=80=9CMo=
reover, Gig3 stockholders could not logically expect to receive $10 per sha=
re of value in exchange.=E2=80=9D

Here is  the opinion. The merger closed in May 2021, when about 71% of Gig3=
=E2=80=99s public shareholders agreed to exchange their shares for shares i=
n the newly public Lightning instead of redeeming at $10 per share. The sto=
ck closed at $0.5161 on Friday. Shareholders who did not redeem =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0who effectively traded $10 for shares worth $0.5161 =E2=80=94=C2=A0su=
ed, claiming that Gig3=E2=80=99s sponsors did the deal not because it was g=
ood for their=C2=A0shareholders (it turned out not to be) but because it go=
t the sponsors $39 million of free stock.=C2=A0Gig3/Lightning tried to have=
 the lawsuit dismissed, but the Chancery Court let it go ahead.=C2=A0
There are some bad facts =E2=80=94=C2=A0Gig3 tried to do a $100+ million PI=
PE deal to raise more money and validate the price it was paying, but ultim=
ately raised only $25 million from a big existing Lighting shareholder, so =
it ended up selling convertible notes at pretty onerous terms; the prospect=
us for the merger had optimistic financial projections that mostly didn=E2=
=80=99t work out =E2=80=94=C2=A0but mostly the problems here are the proble=
ms of any SPAC. In any SPAC, the sponsor has incentives to do a deal, any d=
eal, since she gets millions of dollars of free stock if a deal closes and =
loses the startup costs of the SPAC if it doesn=E2=80=99t. And in any SPAC,=
 the SPAC=E2=80=99s pot of cash is not=C2=A0really=C2=A0worth $10 per share=
 =E2=80=94=C2=A0it=E2=80=99s worth $8 per share or less =E2=80=94=C2=A0so i=
t is hard for the sponsor to find a deal worth $10 per share or more.=C2=A0
Everything that I wrote above is =E2=80=A6=C2=A0correct? =E2=80=A6=C2=A0and=
 =E2=80=A6=C2=A0intuitive? =E2=80=9CIf Gig3 had less than $6 per share to c=
ontribute to the merger,=E2=80=9D then =E2=80=9CGig3 stockholders could not=
 logically expect to receive $10 per share of value in exchange.=E2=80=9D B=
ut that=E2=80=99s just=C2=A0logic.=C2=A0There is some practical sense in wh=
ich, in like 2020, the answer was pretty much =E2=80=9Cehhh there is enough=
 value to go around here, it=E2=80=99s fine, everything goes up, don=E2=80=
=99t worry about how much the sponsor is getting paid or who=E2=80=99s payi=
ng them.=E2=80=9D Now things are tighter, and there is reason to worry.

