<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">SPAC SPAC SPAC</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Simplifying a bit, the way a special purpose a=
cquisition company works is that the sponsor of the SPAC raises a pot of mo=
ney by selling shares to public investors at $10 per share. Say the sponsor=
 offers 20 million shares, so the pot of money has $200 million in it. Then=
 she goes out and looks for a private target company to merge with to take =
it public. Say she finds a private company that is worth $800 million. (The=
 valuation of a private company will always be uncertain, but let=E2=80=99s=
 assume for now that the valuation of=C2=A0<em>this=C2=A0</em>company is ce=
rtain, and that it=E2=80=99s $800 million.) If the target company is worth =
$800 million, and the SPAC is just a pot of money with $200 million in it, =
then the combined company should be worth $1 billion. So the sponsor and th=
e target company negotiate a merger in which the existing shareholders of t=
he target company get 80% of the shares of the combined company ($800 milli=
on worth) and the SPAC shareholders get 20% ($200 million worth). (The merg=
er=C2=A0is sometimes called a =E2=80=9Cde-SPAC merger.=E2=80=9D)=C2=A0The p=
ublic investors in the SPAC, who put in $10 each, end up with publicly trad=
ed shares of the combined company worth $10 each.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If the SPAC sponsor doesn=E2=80=99t find a dea=
l before, typically, the two-year deadline put on the SPAC, she has to give=
 her public shareholders their $200 million back with interest. If she does=
 find a deal, she has to put it to a vote of the public shareholders; they =
can vote it down if they don=E2=80=99t think it=E2=80=99s a good deal. Even=
 if they vote in favor, they can=C2=A0<em>redeem=C2=A0</em>their stock: Ins=
tead of taking new shares in the combined company, the SPAC shareholders ca=
n ask for <em>their </em>$10 back (with interest).=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That is the basic story, but it=C2=A0is too si=
mplified, and=C2=A0in the real world things won=E2=80=99t quite work this w=
ay. In the real world the valuation of the private target company will be u=
ncertain, and there will be a negotiation about how much of the combined co=
mpany the SPAC=E2=80=99s shareholders should get. The SPAC sponsor might re=
asonably say: =E2=80=9CLook, you are a risky private company, your valuatio=
n is uncertain, and I am=C2=A0doing you a favor =E2=80=94=C2=A0I am providi=
ng a service =E2=80=94 by giving you publicly traded stock. You and I both =
think that you are probably worth $800 million, but I want a discount. Let=
=E2=80=99s do this deal <em>as though</em> you were worth $600 million, so =
the SPAC shareholders get 25%=C2=A0of the company, instead of 20%.=E2=80=9D=
 If the target company agrees, and if they=E2=80=99re right that the <em>re=
al=C2=A0</em>value is $800 million, then the public investors will end up w=
ith 25% of a combined company worth $1 billion. They put in $200 million an=
d got back shares worth $250 million; each of their public shares will be w=
orth $12.50. And in fact at the peak of the 2020-2021 SPAC boom, this happe=
ned a lot: SPACs would announce deals with private companies, and their sha=
res would trade up, to $12.50 or higher, because the SPACs were getting a g=
ood deal.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #=
000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-=
bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-col=
or: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Now, things could go the other way. In fact th=
ere was eventually a glut of SPACs looking for deals, and the negotiating l=
everage flipped. The target company=E2=80=99s founder might reasonably say:=
 =E2=80=9CLook, you are a SPAC in a glut of SPACs, you need a deal, and I a=
m=C2=A0doing<em> you </em>a favor=C2=A0by giving you a target. You and I bo=
th think that I am worth $800 million, but I want a premium. Let=E2=80=99s =
do this deal as though I was worth $1 billion, so your SPAC shareholders ge=
t 16.7% of the company instead of 20%.=E2=80=9D Then the SPAC=E2=80=99s pub=
lic shareholders would get shares of the combined company worth $8.33.<a cl=
ass=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-d=
ecoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: =
#000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparen=
t !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>=C2=A0Except that if this happened =E2=80=94 if the SPAC agreed to do a=
 deal at a value that everyone knew made the shares worth less than $10 =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0the shareholders would just say no. They would vote to reject t=
he deal, or at least, they=E2=80=99d redeem their shares: Much better to ge=
t back $10 with interest than keep shares worth $8.33. SPACs can do deals a=
t a discount (if they can talk their targets into those deals!), but not at=
 a premium.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Of course I am still oversimplifying. For one =
thing, I am still assuming that everyone basically knows the valuation of t=
he private company: The SPAC and the target might negotiate for a premium o=
r discount, but the =E2=80=9Creal=E2=80=9D value is transparent to the mark=
et. That=E2=80=99s not really true, and it is not hard to find SPAC deals t=
hat traded up when they were announced and eventually traded down as the re=
al value of the company became clearer. In reality it is not at all uncommo=
n for SPAC shareholders to trade their $10 for shares that ultimately turn =
out to be=C2=A0worth=C2=A0less than that. When that happens, the shareholde=
rs might, in hindsight, feel like they were deceived. The SPAC sponsor anno=
unced the deal with great excitement, the shareholders believed it, they ke=
pt their shares, thinking that they=E2=80=99d be worth way more than $10, a=
nd they turned out to be worth less.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But I have also oversimplified by omitting som=
e important structural elements of SPACs. In fact, when the SPAC sponsor ra=
ises $200 million at the very beginning of this process, she=C2=A0<em>doesn=
=E2=80=99t=C2=A0</em>do it just by selling 20 million shares. She sells 20 =
million =E2=80=9Cunits,=E2=80=9D and each unit consists of (1) one share an=
d (2) some number of=C2=A0<em>warrants</em>, options to buy another share a=
t some higher price. (Generally the warrant exercise price is $11.50, a 15%=
 premium to the initial price of the stock, and each unit comes with a frac=
tion of a warrant, often one-quarter or=C2=A0one-third.) After the SPAC goe=
s public, the warrants and shares will trade separately. Ultimately, if the=
 SPAC closes a deal, each=C2=A0<em>share=C2=A0</em>can be redeemed for $10 =
or roll over into a share of the combined company, but each=C2=A0<em>warran=
t=C2=A0</em>can only roll over to become a warrant of the combined company.=
 And if the SPAC does=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>close a deal, each=C2=A0<em>sh=
are=C2=A0</em>can be redeemed for $10, but each warrant expires worthless.<=
/p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also, when the SPAC sponsor raises $200 millio=
n at the beginning of the process, there are not just 20 million SPAC share=
s outstanding. In fact the SPAC sponsor will generally give herself 20% own=
ership of the SPAC =E2=80=94 5 million shares =E2=80=94=C2=A0for free as a =
reward for her efforts in setting it up and finding a deal.<a class=3D"foot=
note-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !importan=
t; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>=C2=A0If she fails to find a deal, those shares are canceled: She has t=
o return $10 per share to the public shareholders, $200 million total, whic=
h uses up all of the money in the pot, and there=E2=80=99s nothing left for=
 her. (In fact she will <em>lose=C2=A0</em>money, because she paid the SPAC=
=E2=80=99s startup costs, advisory fees etc. out of her own pocket.) But if=
 she does find a deal, her 5 million shares roll over into shares of the co=
mbined company.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">(One more thing that I am omitting is that SPA=
C deals are traditionally done alongside PIPEs, private investments in publ=
ic equity, where the sponsor and/or some other big institutional investors =
put=C2=A0more money into the combined company=C2=A0at $10 per share. I am g=
oing to continue omitting that =E2=80=94=C2=A0and in fact as the SPAC glut =
got shakier PIPEs were=C2=A0not universal =E2=80=94=C2=A0but if there is a =
PIPE it considerably softens some of the criticisms in the rest of this sto=
ry.)</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Now let=E2=80=99s go back to the simple math, =
but with these more realistic facts. The sponsor finds a private company wo=
rth $800 million, and they agree to a merger on exact fair-value terms. The=
 SPAC contributes $200 million, the combined company is worth $1 billion, s=
o the SPAC gets back 20% of the combined company, which is worth $200 milli=
on. But now the SPAC has to divide up that value. There are=C2=A0<em>not=C2=
=A0</em>20 million shares of the SPAC: There are 25 million, the 20 million=
 public shares and the sponsor=E2=80=99s 5 million free shares. Each of the=
se shares is worth $8. The sponsor gets 5 million shares worth $40 million =
for free, but that $40 million comes directly out of the public shareholder=
s=E2=80=99 ownership stake. They put in $10 and get back shares worth $8.</=
p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also there are the warrants. In this stylized =
example, where we know the stock is worth $8 and the warrants are worthless=
 unless the stock gets to $11.50, the warrants aren=E2=80=99t worth much. B=
ut in the real world, where stocks are volatile and value is uncertain, the=
 warrants will have some value, and that value will dilute the other holder=
s of the combined company. The target company might say: =E2=80=9COkay fine=
, we are worth $800 million, you have $200 million, the combined company is=
 worth $1 billion and we will give you 20% of that value. But that 20% has =
to be divided among your shares and your warrants; we are not going to give=
 your=C2=A0<em>shareholders=C2=A0</em>20% of the company and then also let =
your=C2=A0<em>warrantholders=C2=A0</em>exercise their warrants for another =
20%.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-4" style=3D"color: #00000=
0; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-botto=
m-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: t=
ransparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a>=C2=A0That would be unfair. We=E2=80=99ll give your shareholders, say, =
16% of the combined company=E2=80=99s stock, to reflect the fact that if th=
ings go well your warrantholders will get another big chunk of the stock.=
=E2=80=9D (Don=E2=80=99t worry about the exact number =E2=80=94=C2=A0it wil=
l depend on, basically, how valuable you think the warrants are, how close =
they are to being a share of stock =E2=80=94=C2=A0but the point is that you=
 should attribute=C2=A0<em>some=C2=A0</em>value to the SPAC=E2=80=99s warra=
nts, which will reduce the value that you attribute to its stock.)</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">These things are problems. They suggest that i=
f a SPAC ever agrees to a merger at=C2=A0<em>exactly fair value=C2=A0</em>=
=E2=80=94=C2=A0where the SPAC puts in $200 million and gets back exactly $2=
00 million worth of the combined company =E2=80=94=C2=A0then the SPAC=E2=80=
=99s=C2=A0<em>public shareholders=C2=A0</em>are getting hosed. Their $10 in=
vestment turns into stock worth $8 at most, probably $7 or less. Of course =
they can vote no on the deal, and/or redeem their stock, and this math sugg=
ests that they always should, and that if they vote yes they are somehow co=
nfused or deceived.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The simplest=C2=A0solution here is for the SPA=
C to negotiate such a good deal =E2=80=94=C2=A0and for the combined company=
 to perform so well =E2=80=94=C2=A0that the shares are worth $12 anyway. Li=
ke, if the SPAC contributes $200 million and gets back $400 million worth o=
f value, that=E2=80=99s plenty to make sure that the sponsor gets her free =
shares, the warrantholders get their warrants, and the public shareholders =
get shares worth more than $10. In the peak days of SPAC enthusiasm, that k=
ind of worked, through some combination of:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">SPACs seemed like an attractive way to=
 go public, so private companies=C2=A0<em>were=C2=A0</em>willing to merge w=
ith them at=C2=A0discounts;</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">you ne=
eded a PIPE deal alongside the SPAC, so if a deal was going to get=C2=A0don=
e then target companies had to agree on a valuation that made the common sh=
ares worth $10<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-5" style=3D"col=
or: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bo=
rder-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; backgroun=
d-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[5]</span>
</a>;</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">the market was going up gene=
rally;</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">SPAC shareholders were part=
icularly enthusiastic, so they kept bidding up de-SPAC mergers; and</li>=09=
<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">possibly people did not understand this s=
tuff very clearly?</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But over time, as the market stopped rising, S=
PACs became better understood, and a glut of SPACs pursued a smaller univer=
se of good deals, these things became real problems. The deep problem with =
a SPAC is that the SPAC=E2=80=99s sponsor takes out 20% of the value of the=
 money that she raises, and the warrantholders get a cut too, and=C2=A0<em>=
somebody needs to pay them that cut</em>. Either the target company pays it=
 (by giving up more of the company for the SPAC proceeds), or the public SP=
AC shareholders pay it=C2=A0(by getting shares worth $7 for their $10 inves=
tment). Somebody is getting a bad deal.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The argument above is loosely based on a well-=
known=C2=A02020 paper called =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomber=
gbusiness.com/click/30196665.271518/aHR0cHM6Ly9wYXBlcnMuc3Nybi5jb20vc29sMy9=
wYXBlcnMuY2ZtP2Fic3RyYWN0X2lkPTM3MjA5MTk/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB7299ec73"=
 itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"=
color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px;=
 border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color=
: #ccc;">A Sober Look at SPACs</a>,=E2=80=9D by Michael Klausner, Michael O=
hlrogge and Emily Ruan. From the abstract:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We find that costs embedded in the=
 SPAC structure are subtle, opaque, higher than has been previously recogni=
zed, and higher than the cost of an IPO. Although SPACs raise $10.00 per sh=
are from investors in their IPOs, by the time a SPAC merges with a private =
company to take it public, the SPAC holds far less in net cash per share to=
 contribute to the combined company. For SPACs that merged during our prima=
ry sample period of January 2019 through June 2020, mean and median net cas=
h per share were $4.10 and $5.70, respectively. Between June 2020 and Novem=
ber 2021, net cash per share was somewhat higher but far below $10. We find=
 that SPAC costs are not born by the companies they take public, but instea=
d by the SPAC shareholders who hold shares at the time SPACs merge. These i=
nvestors experience steep post-merger losses, while SPAC sponsors profit ha=
ndsomely.=C2=A0</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Intuitively, if the =E2=80=9Cnet cash per shar=
e=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0that is, the money=C2=A0that the SPAC has in its =
pot, divided by the=C2=A0<em>real=C2=A0</em>number of shares including free=
 sponsor shares and warrants =E2=80=94=C2=A0is $5.70, then either target co=
mpanies are getting a bad deal (giving up $10 of value for $5.70 of cash), =
or public SPAC shareholders are getting a bad deal (getting $5.70 of value =
for $10 of cash). And Klausner et al. find that it=E2=80=99s mostly the sha=
reholders getting the bad deal. Their article =E2=80=9Cconcludes by suggest=
ing that the SEC promulgate disclosure requirements specific to SPAC merger=
s that make clear SPACs=E2=80=99=C2=A0costs and sponsors=E2=80=99 incentive=
s.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But that=E2=80=99s just an academic paper. Put=
ting his money where his mouth is, though, Klausner went out to sue some SP=
ACs, and <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30196665.=
271518/aHR0cHM6Ly9uZXdzLmJsb29tYmVyZ2xhdy5jb20vYnVzaW5lc3MtYW5kLXByYWN0aWNl=
L2xhd3N1aXQtdGVzdGluZy10cnVlLXZhbHVlLW9mLXNwYWNzLXN1cnZpdmVzLW1vdGlvbi10by1=
kaXNtaXNz/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB2cbe5cc1" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemsco=
pe=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration=
: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; =
border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  last week he won a r=
ound</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A court ruling Wednesday bolstered research th=
at argues the true worth of blank-check company mergers is often far below =
the typical $10-a-share valuation.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Delaware Chancery Court ruling found that =
the GigCapital3 Inc. special purpose acquisition company must face claims t=
hat public shareholders were denied crucial information, including how much=
 money shares were worth in the purchase of an electric vehicle manufacture=
r.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The GigCapital3 SPAC shareholders couldn=E2=80=
=99t make an informed decision on whether to cash out shares or participate=
 in its purchase of Lightning eMotors, court Vice Chancellor Lori Will rule=
d. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Stanford Law Professor Michael Klausner develo=
ped a financial model that argues the true value of SPAC shares are much lo=
wer than $10-a-share. He brought the court case in August 2021 against GigC=
apital3 alongside lawyers from Grant &amp; Eisenhofer. The suit was a rare =
move for a self-described =E2=80=9Cobscure academic.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In the Gig3 case, the sponsor=E2=80=99s initia=
l $25,000 investment had an implied market value at the time of the merger =
worth $39 million=E2=80=94a 155,900% return, Klausner argued. Sponsors only=
 earn those returns when a deal is completed.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Will=E2=80=99s ruling accepted Klausner=E2=80=
=99s calculations. Part of the information GigCapital3 shareholders didn=E2=
=80=99t receive was that the shares the SPAC used to purchase Lightning eMo=
tors were worth around $5.25 per share=E2=80=94not $10, according to Will.<=
/p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CIf Gig3 had less than $6 per share to=
 contribute to the merger, the proxy=E2=80=99s statement that Gig3 shares w=
ere worth $10 each was false=E2=80=94or at least materially misleading,=E2=
=80=9D she wrote. =E2=80=9CMoreover, Gig3 stockholders could not logically =
expect to receive $10 per share of value in exchange.=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomberg=
business.com/click/30196665.271518/aHR0cHM6Ly9jb3VydHMuZGVsYXdhcmUuZ292L09w=
aW5pb25zL0Rvd25sb2FkLmFzcHg_aWQ9MzQyMjQw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB34d4fd13"=
 itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"=
color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px;=
 border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color=
: #ccc;"> the opinion</a>. The merger closed in May 2021, when about 71% of=
 Gig3=E2=80=99s public shareholders agreed to exchange their shares for sha=
res in the newly public Lightning instead of redeeming at $10 per share. Th=
e stock closed at $0.5161 on Friday. Shareholders who did not redeem =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0who effectively traded $10 for shares worth $0.5161 =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0sued, claiming that Gig3=E2=80=99s sponsors did the deal not because it =
was good for their=C2=A0shareholders (it turned out not to be) but because =
it got <em>the sponsors</em> $39 million of free stock.=C2=A0Gig3/Lightning=
 tried to have the lawsuit dismissed, but the Chancery Court let it go ahea=
d.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There are some bad facts =E2=80=94=C2=A0Gig3 t=
ried to do a $100+ million PIPE deal to raise more money and validate the p=
rice it was paying, but ultimately raised only $25 million from a big exist=
ing Lighting shareholder, so it ended up selling convertible notes at prett=
y onerous terms; the prospectus for the merger had optimistic financial pro=
jections that mostly didn=E2=80=99t work out =E2=80=94=C2=A0but mostly the =
problems here are the problems of any SPAC. In any SPAC, the sponsor has in=
centives to do a deal, any deal, since she gets millions of dollars of free=
 stock if a deal closes and loses the startup costs of the SPAC if it doesn=
=E2=80=99t. And in any SPAC, the SPAC=E2=80=99s pot of cash is not=C2=A0<em=
>really=C2=A0</em>worth $10 per share =E2=80=94=C2=A0it=E2=80=99s worth $8 =
per share or less =E2=80=94=C2=A0so it is hard for the sponsor to find a de=
al worth $10 per share or more.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Everything that I wrote above is =E2=80=A6=C2=
=A0correct? =E2=80=A6=C2=A0and =E2=80=A6=C2=A0intuitive? =E2=80=9CIf Gig3 h=
ad less than $6 per share to contribute to the merger,=E2=80=9D then =E2=80=
=9CGig3 stockholders could not logically expect to receive $10 per share of=
 value in exchange.=E2=80=9D But that=E2=80=99s just=C2=A0<em>logic.</em>=
=C2=A0There is some practical sense in which, in like 2020, the answer was =
pretty much =E2=80=9Cehhh there is enough value to go around here, it=E2=80=
=99s fine, everything goes up, don=E2=80=99t worry about how much the spons=
or is getting paid or who=E2=80=99s paying them.=E2=80=9D Now things are ti=
ghter, and there is reason to worry.</p>
